land, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Workington, Cumberland, England":"Workington, Cumberland, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Castle Kendal, Westmorlandshire, England":"Kendal, Westmorland, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Y, Somme, Picardie, France":"Westmorland, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"1104–1170":"1104–1170","1087–Male":"1087–Deceased","1089–Male":"1089–Deceased","1116–1191":"1116–1191","1069–1150":"1069–1150","1073–1138":"1073–1138","about 1150":"about 1150","1138":"1138","1116":"1116","1104":"1104","1069":"1069","1089":"1089","1087":"1087","ABT 1138":"about 1138","1073":"1073","1150":"1150","1170":"1170","1191":"1191","Kendal, Westmorland, England":"Kendal, Westmorland, England","Kendal, Westmoreland, England":"Kendal, Westmorland, England, United Kingdom","Workington, Cumberland, England":"Workington, Cumberland, England, United Kingdom","Castle Kendal, Westmorlandshire, England":"Kendal, Westmorland, England, United Kingdom","Y, Somme, Picardie, France":"Westmorland, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Baron","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["French, English, Dutch, Polish, Czech, Romanian, and Croatian; Breton (also <b>Le Baron</b>): from Old French <i>barun</i>, <i>baron</i>, Middle English <i>barun</i>, <i>baroun</i>, Middle Dutch <i>baroen</i>, Polish, Czech, Romanian, and dialectal Croatian <i>baron</i> ‘baron’ (i.e. a nobleman ranking below an earl and above a knight), a title of nobility which was in England also awarded to certain freemen of the cities of London and York and of the Cinque Ports. As a surname it is unlikely to be a status name denoting a person of rank. Generally, it referred to service in a baronial household or was acquired as a nickname by a peasant who had ideas above his station or applied to a man showing characteristics of a nobleman. See also 3 and 4 below, compare   Barron   and   Lebaron  .","French: habitational name from (Le) Baron, the name of several places in various parts of France. Compare   Lebaron  .","German: status name for a freeman or baron, from <i>barūn</i> ‘imperial or church official’, a loanword in Middle High German from Old French (see 1 above)."],"variants":[{"name":"Barron","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Jose, Juan, Jesus, Manuel, Francisco, Carlos, Miguel, Raul, Pedro, Ruben, Alfredo, Luis.","Scottish: status name from Scots <i>baron</i>, which in the Highlands denoted a small proprietary landholder. In Angus it alluded specifically to a tenant of one of the small baronies attached to the Abbey of Coupar Angus. The surname was taken by Scottish migrants to Ulster. Compare   Baron  .","Scottish: shortened form of <b>McBarron</b>, from Scottish Gaelic <b>Mac a' Bharain</b> ‘son of the baron’. See   Baron   and 1 above."]},{"name":"Boron","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Polish Krystyna, Edyta, Leszek, Mieczyslaw, Mieczyslawa, Wladyslaw.","Polish (<b>Boroń</b>): from a pet form of the personal names <i>Borzysław</i> or <i>Borzymir</i>, formed with the element <i>bor</i> ‘to fight’ (from Old Slavic <i>boriti se</i>).","French: habitational name from a place so called in Franche-Comté."]},{"name":"Baro","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Mario, Manuel, Ana, Angel, Carlos, Cesar, Fernando, Jesus, Jose, Orlando, Ramon, Rosalia.  Italian Guido, Angelo, Carmelo, Federico, Lucio.","Catalan (<b>Baró</b>): status name from <i>baró</i> ‘free man, baron’ (see   Baron   1), or a habitational name from a place so named.","Hungarian (<b>Báró</b>): status name from <i>báró</i> ‘baron’. In the form <b>Baró</b>, it could be from a pet form of the personal names <i>Barabás</i> (see   Barabas  ) or <i>Bertalan</i>."]},{"name":"Barona","meanings":["Spanish: from the feminine form of <b>Barón</b> ‘baron’ (see   Baron  ), applied as a nickname or as an occupational name for a member of the household of a baroness.","Italian: probably from the feminine form of   Barone  . The name is concentrated in Sondrio province (Lombardy)."]},{"name":"Barren","meanings":["English: probably a variant of   Baron   or   Barran  ."]}]},{"name":"Kendal","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (northwestern): variant of   Kendall  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Kendall","meanings":["English: habitational name from Kendal in Cumbria, which takes its name from the river Kent + Old Norse <i>dalr</i> ‘valley’, or from the valley of the river Kent itself.","English (of Welsh origin): from an Anglicized form of the Welsh personal name <i>Cynddelw</i>, which was borne by a famous 12th-century Welsh poet. It probably derives from a Celtic word meaning ‘exalted, high’ + <i>delw</i> ‘image, effigy’."]}]},{"name":"Gilbert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Old French name of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>gisil</i> ‘pledge’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’. It was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to Britain. This was the name of the founder of the only native British religious order (abolished at the Dissolution of the Monasteries),  St Gilbert  of Sempringham (  ?1083–1189 ), in whose honour it is still sometimes bestowed, especially among Roman Catholics. It gained a wider currency in the 19th century."],"variants":[]},{"name":"LANCASTER","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from Lancaster in northwestern England, which is recorded as <i>Loncastre</i> in 1086. The place takes its name from the river Lune + Old English <i>ceaster</i> ‘city, Roman fortification’ (from Latin <i>castra</i> ‘legionary camp’). The river name is probably British, perhaps related to Gaelic <i>slán</i> ‘healthy’, ‘salubrious’."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Gilbert LANCASTER FITZKETEL de Tallenbois Baron Kendal was born in 1104, in Workington, Cumberland, England, United Kingdom, his father, Ketel fitz Eldred, was 36 and his mother, Christiana de Taillebois Baroness of Kendal, was 31. He had at least 1 son. He died in 1170, in Kendal, Westmorland, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 66."},"et":{"1104–1170":"1104–1170","1087–Male":"1087–Surnud","1089–Male":"1089–Surnud","1116–1191":"1116–1191","1069–1150":"1069–1150","1073–1138":"1073–1138","about 1150":"umbes 1150","1138":"1138","1116":"1116","1104":"1104","1069":"1069","1089":"1089","1087":"1087","ABT 1138":"umbes 1138","1073":"1073","1150":"1150","1170":"1170","1191":"1191","Kendal, Westmorland, England":"Kendal, Westmorland, England","Kendal, Westmoreland, England":"Kendal, Westmorland, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Workington, Cumberland, England":"Workington, Cumberland, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Castle Kendal, Westmorlandshire, England":"Kendal, Westmorland, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Y, Somme, Picardie, France":"Westmorland, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1104–1170":"1104–1170","1087–Male":"1087–Kuollut","1089–Male":"1089–Kuollut","1116–1191":"1116–1191","1069–1150":"1069–1150","1073–1138":"1073–1138","about 1150":"noin 1150","1138":"1138","1116":"1116","1104":"1104","1069":"1069","1089"